<br>
Another thing they do well there is that the moderators all have a link to the FAQ section of the site.  I think Whizbang had a similar link in his sig for a while.  The downside is that in their case they'd need to include their sig in every post, but the result will mean more chances for the truly new to find a place to start on the boards.  Sifting through pages of posts can be overwhelming, and I bet search just doesn't always get the results one craves.<br>
<br>
Finally, when someone like Absor or another Sony rep makes a post on the board I tend to take notice.  Although I suspect they would politely refuse, would it be possible to have their names appear in gold or some other color that stands out from the rest? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=artillis>Artillis</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>Enjoys Sheep Erotica</span><br>  Posts: 1799<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/7/03 11:36:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=26402.topic&index=56>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: suggestions</span><hr size=1> I don't see a need for a &quot;newbie&quot; forum.  Most newb questions can be answered in the guides.  Those that can't can easily be answered in general discusion.<br>
<br>
Why make a whole new thread for newb questions when you can just make a rule that you should check guides first before asking a question.  And put in the guides section a general guide that is an FAQ on newb stuff.  Heck even make a sticky to the guide in the rules section and also put a stickied thread at the top of the general section that tells people to read the rules before posting and have a link to the rules in that thread.<br>
<br>
That way when people come to the site and go to the general forum they can read the thread that there supposed to read before posting they will read the rules and also check the guides hopefully before asking simple already answered 50 thousand time questions.  Those that don't do this can have their thread locked with a link to either the guides or a link to the stickied post on reading the rules or bolth.<br>
<br>
